The paper deals with dynamic data structures and graph problems, which are typically studied in the computer science sub-categories of data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational geometry (cs.CG), discrete optimization (cs.DL), and graph theory (cs.GT). Given that the paper focuses on retroactive data structures for graph problems, it is most likely to be classified under cs.DS and cs.DM. However, since the paper also involves algorithms for connectivity and minimum spanning forest, which are classic graph theory problems, it could also be classified under cs.GT. Finally, the paper's focus on upper and lower bounds suggests that it could be classified under cs.DL, while its use of geometric concepts (e.g., Voronoi diagrams) suggests that it could be classified under cs.CG.
